[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Each connector is a pluggable *component* identified by a URI, giving a uniform programming model across message brokers (Kafka, JMS), REST and SOAP APIs, databases (JDBC), file protocols (FTP, SFTP), cloud services (AWS, Azure, Google Cloud), and enterprise applications such as SAP and Salesforce.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Routes can also be designed visually using the open-source tools Kaoto and Apache Camel Karavan.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Camel is an embeddable library rather than a standalone server.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] It runs on Spring Boot, Quarkus, or standalone via its own CLI, and deploys as a standard Java application — as a JAR, a container image, or on Kubernetes.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The Apache Camel project was created by James Strachan, who pushed the first commit — 42 files across two modules (*camel-core* and *camel-jms*) — on March 19, 2007.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Version 1.0 was released on June 27, 2007.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The project drew on ideas from the Enterprise Integration Patterns book and was influenced by earlier integration projects including Apache ServiceMix and Apache ActiveMQ.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] In 2010, FuseSource was founded as a commercial company focused on Apache Camel, ActiveMQ, and ServiceMix.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] FuseSource was acquired by Progress Software in 2011 and subsequently by Red Hat in 2012.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Red Hat productized Apache Camel as Red Hat Fuse (later renamed to Red Hat build of Apache Camel), providing commercial support and enterprise distribution.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Through the 2010s, the component catalog grew as new protocols and cloud services gained adoption.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Components for AWS arrived in 2011, Kafka in 2014, and Spring Boot in 2014.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The 2.x release line ran for over a decade (2009–2021) and produced 25 minor releases and 96 patch releases.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] In 2018, the Apache Camel K subproject was created to run Camel integrations natively on Kubernetes using a dedicated operator.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] In 2019, Camel Quarkus was introduced to bring Camel to the Quarkus runtime with ahead-of-time compilation support.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Camel 3.0 was released on November 28, 2019 — the first major version in ten years — with a modularised core (split from one JAR into 33) and Java 11 support.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] A YAML DSL for defining routes as declarative configuration was added in 2021.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Camel 4.0, released on August 14, 2023, migrated the framework from javax to Jakarta EE APIs, required Java 17, and removed deprecated components to align with modern runtimes such as Quarkus and Spring Boot 3.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] As of 2026, the project supports Model Context Protocol (MCP) for AI agent tool connectivity and A2A (Agent-to-Agent protocol) for inter-agent communication, positioning Camel as an integration runtime for AI agent architectures.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Apache Camel's architecture is based on the concept of *routes* — sequences of processing steps that move messages from a source (*consumer*) to a destination (*producer*).
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Routes are defined using one of several DSLs (Java, XML, YAML) and can apply Enterprise Integration Patterns such as content-based router, message filter, aggregator, splitter, and dead letter channel.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Each external system is accessed through a *component*, which provides a URI-based endpoint for sending or receiving messages.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] With over 350 components, Camel supports a wide range of protocols and APIs without requiring custom adapter code.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The core abstractions — *Processor*, *Exchange*, and *Endpoint* — have remained stable since the project's first commit.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The central routing pattern, expressed as `from("source").to("destination")` in the Java DSL, has been unchanged since 2007 across four major versions.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The framework is modular — applications include only the components they need, keeping the runtime lightweight.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] A minimal Camel application can start in under one second when using Quarkus native compilation.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Apache Camel is one of the larger projects at the Apache Software Foundation by commit volume.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The project's Git repository contains approximately 100,000 commits from over 1,500 contributors, with corporate email domains from over 450 distinct organizations appearing in the commit history.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The repository on GitHub has over 6,200 stars.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The Stack Overflow tag *apache-camel* has over 11,700 questions.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The project has published 272 GA releases to Maven Central since 2007 and has shipped 10 or more releases every year since 2011.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Of the 56,000+ Java source files in the repository, 39% are test files.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The project's bug tracker shows 7,070 bugs resolved out of 7,081 reported (99.8%) with a median resolution time of one day sustained over 17 of 19 years.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] The project maintains multiple long-term support (LTS) release lines simultaneously and publishes migration guides for major version upgrades.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Third-party technology tracking services independently detect Apache Camel usage across thousands of companies.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Enlyft reports over 8,600 companies using Apache Camel.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Apache Camel is used in production across a range of industries.
[src:apache-camel/apache-camel] Several commercial integration platforms use Camel as their underlying runtime engine, including SAP Integration Suite and Huawei Cloud ROMA.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise application integration is an integration framework composed of a collection of technologies and services which form a middleware or "middleware framework" to enable integration of systems and applications across an enterprise.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Many types of business software such as supply chain management applications, ERP systems, CRM applications for managing customers, business intelligence applications, payroll, and human resources systems typically cannot communicate with one another in order to share data or business rules.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] For this reason, such applications are sometimes referred to as islands of automation or information silos.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] This lack of communication leads to inefficiencies, wherein identical data are stored in multiple locations, or straightforward processes are unable to be automated.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Applications can be linked either at the back-end via APIs or (seldom) the front-end (GUI).
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] The various systems that need to be linked together may reside on different operating systems, use different database solutions or computer languages, or different date and time formats, or could be legacy systems that are no longer supported by the vendor who originally created them.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] In some cases, such systems are dubbed "stovepipe systems" because they consist of components that have been jammed together in a way that makes it very hard to modify them in any way.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] If integration is applied without following a structured EAI approach, point-to-point connections grow across an organization.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Dependencies are added on an impromptu basis, resulting in a complex structure that is difficult to maintain.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] This is commonly referred to as spaghetti, an allusion to the programming equivalent of spaghetti code.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] For example, the number of connections needed to have fully meshed point-to-point connections, with n points, is given by ${\tbinom {n}{2}}={\tfrac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ (see binomial coefficient).
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Thus, for ten applications to be fully integrated point-to-point, ${\tfrac {10\times 9}{2}}=45$ point-to-point connections are needed, following a quadratic growth pattern.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] However, the number of connections within organizations does not necessarily grow according to the square of the number of points.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] In general, the number of connections to any point is only limited by the number of other points in an organization, but can be significantly smaller in principle.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] EAI can also increase coupling between systems and therefore increase management overhead and costs.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] EAI is not just about sharing data between applications but also focuses on sharing both business data and business processes.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] A middleware analyst attending to EAI will often look at the system of systems.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] This section describes common design patterns for implementing EAI, including integration, access and lifetime patterns.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] These are abstract patterns and can be implemented in many different ways.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] There are many other patterns commonly used in the industry, ranging from high-level abstract design patterns to highly specific implementation patterns.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Here, the EAI system acts as the go-between or broker between multiple applications.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Whenever an interesting event occurs in an application (for instance, new information is created or a new transaction completed) an integration module in the EAI system is notified.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] The module then propagates the changes to other relevant applications.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] In this case, the EAI system acts as the overarching facade across multiple applications.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] All event calls from the 'outside world' to any of the applications are front-ended by the EAI system.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] The EAI system is configured to expose only the relevant information and interfaces of the underlying applications to the outside world, and performs all interactions with the underlying applications on behalf of the requester.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Both patterns are often used concurrently.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] The same EAI system could be keeping multiple applications in sync (mediation), while servicing requests from external users against these applications (federation).
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] EAI supports both asynchronous (fire and forget) and synchronous access patterns, the former being typical in the mediation case and the latter in the federation case.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] There are two major topologies: hub-and-spoke, and bus.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Each has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] In the hub-and-spoke model, the EAI system is at the center (the hub), and interacts with the applications via the spokes.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] In the bus model, the EAI system is the bus (or is implemented as a resident module in an already existing message bus or message-oriented middleware).
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Most large enterprises use zoned networks to create a layered defense against network oriented threats.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] For example, an enterprise typically has a credit card processing (PCI-compliant) zone, a non-PCI zone, a data zone, a DMZ zone to proxy external user access, and an IWZ zone to proxy internal user access.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Applications need to integrate across multiple zones.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] The **Hub and spoke** model would work better in this case.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] , message bus) or implemented as a stand-alone program (i.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] e., does not use any middleware), acting as its own middleware.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] These are programs that know how to interact with an underlying business application.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] The adapter performs one-way communication(unidirectional), performing requests from the hub against the application, and notifying the hub when an event of interest occurs in the application (a new record inserted, a transaction completed, etc.).
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Adapters can be specific to an application (e.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] g., built against the application vendor's client libraries) or specific to a class of applications (e.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] The adapter could reside in the same process space as the bus/hub or execute in a remote location and interact with the hub/bus through industry-standard protocols such as message queues, web services, or even use a proprietary protocol.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] allow adapters to be created in a vendor-neutral manner.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] To avoid every adapter having to convert data to/from every other application's formats, EAI systems usually stipulate an application-independent (or common) data format.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] The EAI system usually provides a data transformation service as well to help convert between application-specific and common formats.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] This is done in two steps: the adapter converts information from the application's format to the bus's common format.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Then, semantic transformations are applied to this (converting zip codes to city names, splitting/merging objects from one application into objects in the other applications, and so on).
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] An EAI system could be participating in multiple concurrent integration operations at any given time, each type of integration being processed by a different integration module.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Integration modules subscribe to events of specific types and process notifications that they receive when these events occur.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] that conform to the EAI system's specifications.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Currently, there are many variations of thought on what constitutes the best infrastructure, component model, and standards structure for Enterprise Application Integration.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] An independent data model based on a standard data structure, also known as a canonical data model.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] It appears that XML and the use of XML style sheets have become the *de facto* and in some cases *de jure* standard for this uniform business language.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] A connector, or agent model where each vendor, application, or interface can build a single component that can speak natively to that application and communicate with the centralized broker.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] A system model that defines the APIs, data flow and rules of engagement to the system such that components can be built to interface with it in a standardized way.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Although other approaches like connecting at the database or user-interface level have been explored, they have not been found to scale or be able to adjust.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Individual applications can publish messages to the centralized broker and subscribe to receive certain messages from that broker.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Each application only requires one connection to the broker.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] This central control approach can be extremely scalable and highly evolvable.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise Application Integration is related to middleware technologies such as message-oriented middleware (MOM), and data representation technologies such as XML or JSON.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Other EAI technologies involve using web services as part of service-oriented architecture as a means of integration.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise Application Integration tends to be data centric.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] In the near future, it will come to include content integration and business processes.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] In 2003 it was reported that 70% of all EAI projects fail.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Most of these failures are not due to the software itself or technical difficulties, but due to management issues.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Integration Consortium European Chairman Steve Craggs has outlined the seven main pitfalls undertaken by companies using EAI systems and explains solutions to these problems.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Shortage of EAI experts: EAI requires knowledge of many issues and technical aspects.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Competing standards: Within the EAI field, the paradox is that EAI standards themselves are not universal.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] EAI is a tool paradigm: EAI is not a tool, but rather a system and should be implemented as such.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Building interfaces is an art: Engineering the solution is not sufficient.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Solutions need to be negotiated with user departments to reach a common consensus on the final outcome.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] A lack of consensus on interface designs leads to excessive effort to map between various systems' data requirements.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Loss of detail: Information that seemed unimportant at an earlier stage may become crucial later.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-application-integration] Accountability: Since so many departments have many conflicting requirements, there should be clear accountability for the system's final structure.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-integration-patterns] The pattern language presented in the book consists of 65 patterns structured into 9 categories, which largely follow the flow of a message from one system to the next through channels, routing, and transformations.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-integration-patterns] The book includes an icon-based pattern language, sometimes nicknamed "GregorGrams" after one of the authors.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-integration-patterns] Excerpts from the book (short pattern descriptions) are available on the supporting website (see External links).
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-integration-patterns] The pattern language continues to be relevant as of today, for instance in cloud application development and integration, and in the internet of things.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-integration-patterns] In 2015, the two book authors reunited—for the first time since the publication of the book—for a retrospective and interview in *IEEE Software*.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-integration-patterns] Enterprise Integration Patterns are implemented in many open source integration solutions.
[src:apache-camel/enterprise-integration-patterns] Notable implementations include Spring Integration, Apache Camel, Red Hat Fuse, Mule ESB and Guaraná DSL.
[src:apache-camel/manual] Apache Camel™ is a versatile open-source integration framework based on known Enterprise Integration Patterns.
[src:apache-camel/manual] Camel empowers you to define routing and mediation rules in a variety of domain-specific languages (DSL, such as Java, XML, Groovy, and YAML).
[src:apache-camel/manual] This means you get smart completion of routing rules in your IDE, whether in a Java or XML editor.
[src:apache-camel/manual] For a deeper and better understanding of Apache Camel, an Introduction is provided.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] MOM allows application modules to be distributed over heterogeneous platforms and reduces the complexity of developing applications that span multiple operating systems and network protocols.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The middleware creates a distributed communications layer that insulates the application developer from the details of the various operating systems and network interfaces.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Application programming interfaces (APIs) that extend across diverse platforms and networks are typically provided by MOM.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] This middleware layer allows software components (applications, servlets, and other components) that have been developed independently and might run on different networked platforms to interact with one another.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Applications distributed on different network nodes use the application interface to communicate.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, by providing an administrative interface, this new, virtual system of interconnected applications can be made fault tolerant and secure.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] MOM provides software elements that reside in all communicating components of a client/server architecture and typically support asynchronous calls between the client and server applications.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] MOM reduces the involvement of application developers with the complexity of the master-slave nature of the client/server mechanism.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] All these models make it possible for one software component to affect the behavior of another component over a network.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] They are different in that RPC- and ORB-based middleware create systems of tightly coupled components, whereas MOM-based systems allow for a loose coupling of components.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In an RPC- or ORB-based system, when one procedure calls another, it must wait for the called procedure to return before it can do anything else.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In these mostly synchronous messaging models, the middleware functions partly as a super-linker, locating the called procedure on a network and using network services to pass function or method parameters to the procedure and then to return results.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Note that Object request brokers also support fully asynchronous messaging via oneway invocations.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Central reasons for using a message-based communications protocol include its ability to store (buffer), route, or transform messages while conveying them from senders to receivers.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Another advantage of messaging provider-mediated messaging between clients is that by adding an administrative interface, you can monitor and tune performance.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Client applications are thus effectively relieved of every problem except that of sending, receiving, and processing messages.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] It is up to the code that implements the MOM system and up to the administrator to resolve issues like interoperability, reliability, security, scalability, and performance.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Using a MOM system, a client makes an API call to send a message to a destination managed by the provider.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The call invokes provider services to route and deliver the message.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Once it has sent the message, the client can continue to do other work, confident that the provider retains the message until a receiving client retrieves it.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The message-based model, coupled with the mediation of the provider, makes it possible to create a system of loosely coupled components.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] MOM comprises a category of inter-application communication software that generally relies on asynchronous message-passing, as opposed to a request-response architecture.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In asynchronous systems, message queues provide temporary storage when the destination program is busy or not connected.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, most asynchronous MOM systems provide persistent storage to back up the message queue.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] This means that the sender and receiver do not need to connect to the network at the same time (asynchronous delivery), and problems with intermittent connectivity are solved.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] It also means that should the receiver application fail for any reason, the senders can continue unaffected, as the messages they send will simply accumulate in the message queue for later processing when the receiver restarts.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Many message-oriented middleware implementations depend on a message queue system.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations permit routing logic to be provided by the messaging layer itself, while others depend on client applications to provide routing information or allow for a mix of both paradigms.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations make use of broadcast or multicast distribution paradigms.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In a message-based middleware system, the message received at the destination need not be identical to the message originally sent.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] A MOM system with built-in intelligence can transform messages and route to match the requirements of the sender or of the recipient.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In conjunction with the routing and broadcast/multicast facilities, one application can send a message in its own native format, and two or more other applications may each receive a copy of the message in their own native format.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Many modern MOM systems provide sophisticated message transformation (or mapping) tools which allow programmers to specify transformation rules applicable to a simple GUI drag-and-drop operation.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The primary disadvantage of many message-oriented middleware systems is that they require an extra component in the architecture, the message transfer agent (message broker).
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] As with any system, adding another component can lead to reductions in performance and reliability, and can also make the system as a whole more difficult and expensive to maintain.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, many inter-application communications have an intrinsically synchronous aspect, with the sender specifically wanting to wait for a reply to a message before continuing (see real-time computing and near-real-time for extreme cases).
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Because message-based communication inherently functions asynchronously, it may not fit well in such situations.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] That said, most MOM systems have facilities to group a request and a response as a single pseudo-synchronous transaction.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] With a synchronous messaging system, the calling function does not return until the called function has finished its task.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In a loosely coupled asynchronous system, the calling client can continue to load work upon the recipient until the resources needed to handle this work are depleted and the called component fails.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Of course, these conditions can be minimized or avoided by monitoring performance and adjusting message flow, but this is work that is not needed with a synchronous messaging system.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The important thing is to understand the advantages and liabilities of each kind of system.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Each system is appropriate for different kinds of tasks.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Sometimes, a combination of the two kinds of systems is required to obtain the desired behavior.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Historically, there was a lack of standards governing the use of message-oriented middleware that has caused problems.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Most of the major vendors have their own implementations, each with its own application programming interface (API) and management tools.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] One of the long-standing standards for message-oriented middleware is X/Open group's XATMI specification (Distributed Transaction Processing: The XATMI Specification) which standardizes API for interprocess communications.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Known implementations for this API is ATR Baltic's Enduro/X middleware and Oracle's Tuxedo.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) is an approved OASIS and ISO standard that defines the protocol and formats used between participating application components, so implementations are interoperable.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] It also supports transaction management, queuing, distribution, security, management, clustering, federation and heterogeneous multi-platform support.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Java applications that use AMQP are typically written in Java JMS.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Other implementations provide APIs for C#, C++, PHP, Python, Ruby, and other programming languages.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The High Level Architecture (HLA IEEE 1516) is an Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) and Simulation Interoperability Standards Organization (SISO) standard for simulation interoperability.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] It defines a set of services, provided through an API in C++ or Java.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The services offer publish/subscribe-based information exchange, based on a modular Federation Object Model.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] There are also services for coordinated data exchange and time advance, based on logical simulation time, as well as synchronization points.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Additional services provide transfer of ownership, data distribution optimizations and monitoring and management of participating Federates (systems).
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The MQ Telemetry Transport (MQTT) is an ISO standard (ISO/IEC PRF 20922) supported by the OASIS organization.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] It provides a lightweight publish/subscribe reliable messaging transport protocol on top of TCP/IP suitable for communication in M2M/IoT contexts where a small code footprint is required and/or network bandwidth is at a premium.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The Object Management Group's Data Distribution Service (DDS) provides message-oriented Publish/Subscribe (P/S) middleware standard that aims to enable scalable, real-time, dependable, high-performance and interoperable data exchanges between publishers and subscribers.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The standard provides interfaces to C++, C++11, C, Ada, Java, and Ruby.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The eXtensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP) is a communications protocol for message-oriented middleware based on Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Designed to be extensible, the protocol has also been used for publish-subscribe systems, signalling for VoIP, video, file transfer, gaming, Internet of Things applications such as the smart grid, and social networking services.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Unlike most instant messaging protocols, XMPP is defined in an open standard and uses an open systems approach of development and application, by which anyone may implement an XMPP service and interoperate with other organizations' implementations.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Because XMPP is an open protocol, implementations can be developed using any software license; although many server, client, and library implementations are distributed as free and open-source software, many freeware and proprietary software implementations also exist.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed an XMPP working group in 2002 to formalize the core protocols as an IETF instant messaging and presence technology.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] The XMPP Working group produced four specifications (RFC 3920, RFC 3921, RFC 3922, RFC 3923), which were approved as Proposed Standards in 2004.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In 2011, RFC 3920 and RFC 3921 were superseded by RFC 6120 and RFC 6121 respectively, with RFC 6122 specifying the XMPP address format.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] In addition to these core protocols standardized at the IETF, the XMPP Standards Foundation (formerly Jabber Software Foundation) is active in developing open XMPP extensions.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] XMPP-based software is deployed widely across the Internet, according to the XMPP Standards Foundation, and forms the basis for the Department of Defense (DoD) Unified Capabilities Framework.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] A similar effort is with the actively evolving OpenMAMA project, which aims to provide a common API, especially to C clients.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] As of August 2012, it is mainly appropriate for distributing market-oriented data (e.g. stock quotes) over pub-sub middleware.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Message queues allow the exchange of information between distributed applications.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] A message queue can reside in memory or disk storage.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Messages stay in the queue until the time they are processed by a service consumer.
[src:apache-camel/message-oriented-middleware] Through the message queue, the application can be implemented independently - they do not need to know each other's position, or continue to implement procedures to remove the need for waiting to receive this message.
[src:apache-camel/what-is-camel] Apache Camel ™ is a versatile open-source integration framework based on known Enterprise Integration Patterns.
[src:apache-camel/what-is-camel] Camel empowers you to define routing and mediation rules in a variety of domain-specific languages (DSL, such as Java, XML, and YAML).
[src:apache-camel/what-is-camel] This means you get smart completion of routing rules in your IDE.
[src:apache-camel/what-is-camel] Apache Camel uses URIs to work directly with any kind of transport or messaging model such as HTTP, Kafka, JMS, Netty or AWS S3, as well as pluggable Components and Data Format options.
[src:apache-camel/what-is-camel] Apache Camel is a small library with minimal dependencies for easy embedding in any Java application.
[src:apache-camel/what-is-camel] Apache Camel lets you work with the same API regardless which kind of transport is used — so learn the API once and you can interact with all the Components provided out-of-box.
[src:apache-camel/what-is-camel] Apache Camel provides support for Bean Binding and seamless integration with popular frameworks such as Spring.
[src:apache-camel/what-is-camel] Camel also has extensive support for unit testing your routes.
